Abeautifulfuture
JERUSALEM – With my nearly 90 years of life, I cannot recall a time when the past was so insignificant for political decision-making.
No significant developments of the present were predicted by anyone.
Experts did examine the past, but due to their entanglement in old paradigms, they could not derive the future from it.
Given the dynamic complexity of today's world, where events depend more on each other due to a scientifically grounded and rapidly changing global economy, we cannot predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation, which cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and state leaders is waning. In today's global economy, it is not politicians but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The global economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine the outcome because science and technology are boundless.
Global corporations want to pursue their business worldwide, which on one hand undermines sovereignty, but on the other hand weakens racism, prejudices, and significantly also nationalism.
Due to this change, the fate of this world now lies in the hands of a younger generation. They are more technologically adept than their parents and are connected to each other through social networks that transcend national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google wield greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people also form the vanguard of emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring," the tent protests in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia do not mark a clash of cultures, but a battle of generations.
The young generation knows that the way states and economies are currently run is unsuitable for the new times.
However, there are political "jumpers-on" who seek to exploit this latest awakening. But not through the further development of an agenda of freedom, but through the introduction of new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, primarily Islamist extremists are taking over the protests of the young generation and stealing their revolution from them.
Israel has positively reacted to the will of the young generation, but should not interfere in the events of the Arab world.
We are at the heart of the rebelling youths and their legitimate yearning for freedom and basic rights, which should allow them to make their voices heard, choose their political leadership, and earn a living.
The Israelis await the day when their country is no longer the only democracy in the region, because existing as an island of prosperity in a sea of poverty is unnatural.
But there is a serious concern that politically well-organized extremists will try to win control over less well-organized liberals in elections and thus prevent peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists cannot offer real solutions to the fundamental problems of the region.
The current social upheavals threaten their lifestyle, which includes the discrimination of women and a ban on modern education.
However, only fundamental reforms of established authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example when it comes to achieving economic prosperity and social freedom, because its success is founded on the fact that the country had absolutely nothing at the beginning.
When we returned home, we were rich in history but poor in natural resources.
We could only rely on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. That is why we have the highest percentage of scientists and patents per capita today.
About 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high technology.
We use less water and still have higher yields per square meter of arable land than any other country in the world.
What Israel achieves, others can achieve as well.
We are gladly willing to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Primarily, we must do everything in our power to end the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to rule another people, and this is not Israel's destiny.
We are genuinely interested in creating a Palestinian state that exists peacefully side by side with Israel – the democratic state of the Jewish people.
Für uns ist Frieden sowohl ein moralischer Imperativ als auch eine nationale Sicherheitsstrategie, denn die Lösung des Konflikts würde helfen, die Region durch Neutralisierung der Extremisten zu stabilisieren, die darauf aus sind, die Bürgerbewegungen zu manipulieren, um ihre radikale Agenda voranzutreiben.
Die internationale Gemeinschaft kann diese Bestrebungen durch Anreize für jene Länder unterstützen, die nach Freiheit und Fortschritt streben.
Gleichzeitig müssen entschiedene und wegweisende politische Maßnahmen gegen die Extremisten ergriffen werden.
Besonders der Iran ist eine Quelle moralischer Verkommenheit, wo man dem Extremismus Vorschub leistet und Reformen blockiert. Man zerschlägt legitime Proteste der eigenen Bürger und arbeitet gegen die tapferen Syrer, die momentan für ihre Freiheit kämpfen.
Außerdem bedient sich der Iran mehrerer Stellvertreter, um Terror gegen moderate Kräfte in der Palästinensischen Behörde, im Libanon und dem Irak anzuzetteln.
Gelingt es dem Iran, sich Atomwaffen anzueignen, könnten die Führer des Landes damit den Nahen und Mittleren Osten erschüttern und noch mehr Extremismus und Gewalt schüren.
Israel wird sich verteidigen, wenn der Iran weiterhin die Zerstörung Israels fordert.
Doch nicht nur Israel ist bedroht. Der Iran ist eine Gefahr für den Frieden und die Stabilität auf der ganzen Welt.
Die Demokratien dieser Welt haben erklärt, dass sie es dem Iran nicht gestatten werden, in den Besitz von Atomwaffen zu gelangen. Es ist ihre Pflicht, diesem Bekenntnis nachzukommen, bevor das nicht mehr möglich ist.
Über diese kurzfristigen Herausforderungen hinaus haben wir alle die Pflicht, die Art und Weise, wie wir unsere Kinder auf den Umgang mit der Welt von heute vorbereiten, grundlegend zu ändern.
To a time where the past is irrelevant for predicting the future, education must offer all children the opportunity to fulfill their potential.
Today's teachers should motivate our children towards creativity and innovation.
Self-realization is just as important as free expression of opinion.
I write this article at 88 years of age, but not because I have learned from experience.
On the contrary: experience is overvalued and often restricts the courage needed to face the future and create an unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back doesn't make sense.
